{{Infobox mountain | name = Saka Haphong | other_name = Mowdok Taung | photo = Saka Haphong.jpg | photo_caption = Saka Haphong | elevation_m = 1052 | elevation_ref = <ref name="peakbagger">{{cite peakbagger|pid=10949|name=Mowdok Mual, Bangladesh|accessdate=2014-07-28}}{{self-published source|date=November 2015}}</ref> | prominence_m = 820 | prominence_ref = <ref>[[SRTM]] data in agreement with 1:200,000 Soviet topographic mapping</ref> | map = Bangladesh | map_caption = Location in Bangladesh (on the border with Burma) | label_position = left | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | location = [[Bangladesh]]–[[Burma]] border | range = Mowdok range | coordinates = {{coord|21|47|19|N|92|36|31|E|type:mountain_region:BD_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range_coordinates = | coordinates_ref = | topo = | type = [[Mountain]] | age = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Saka Haphong''' (also '''Mowdok Taung''' or '''Tlang Moy''') is a peak in [[Bangladesh]], often considered the highest point of the country, with an elevation of 1,052&nbsp;metres (3,451&nbsp;ft).<ref>Bao-Rong Lu, General information of the areas visited and the collecting routes, [http://www.irri.org/GRC/Biodiversity/Pdffiles/BGDpdf/bgd3.pdf/ A Report On BRRI-IRRI Cooperative Collection of Wild Oryza Species In Bangladesh]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, page 5, International Rice Research Institute, October 1529, 1998{{Dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://highpointguides.com/catalog/index.php?manufacturers_id=10&osCsid=8c8694c8a089ad05118870df688a00ff/ Country-wise highest points], HighPoint.com{{Dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref> Located on the Bangladesh–[[Burma]] border, it is situated between [[Thanchi Upazila|Thanchi]], [[Bandarban]], Bangladesh and the [[Chin State]] of Burma.
Saka Haphong is not officially the highest peak of Bangladesh,<ref>{{cite book |last=Chowdhury |first=Masud Hasan |year=2012 |chapter=Physiography |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Physiography |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html |title=Bangladesh |website=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA}}</ref> but maps and other data indicate there are no higher peaks within the country.<ref name="peakbagger"/> In February 2006 a GPS reading of 1,064 metres was recorded on this summit by English adventurer [[Ginge Fullen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gingefullen.com/peaksclimbed.htm |title=World peaks climbed |website=Ginge Fullen |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729022014/http://www.gingefullen.com/peaksclimbed.htm |archive-date=29 July 2014}}{{self-published source|date=November 2015}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=November 2015}} The location he recorded, 21°47′11″N 92°36′36″E / 21.78639°N 92.61°E, accurately matches the location given by Russian topographic mapping<ref>{{cite web |url=http://download.maps.vlasenko.net/smtm200/g-46-26.jpg/ |title=Relevant section of the Topographic Map |date=1965 |website=Топографическая карта Украины, России, Беларуси |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501175606/http://download.maps.vlasenko.net/smtm200/g-46-26.jpg |archive-date=1 May 2013}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2015}} and [[SRTM]] data, although these sources show its height to be slightly lower, at 1,052 metres. Recently two trekking clubs counted the height of Saka Haphong as 3,488 and 3,461 feet respectively.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 February 2011 |title='Second highest hill' spotted by 4 youths |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=175791/ |newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref> Any of these figures would make it the highest mountain in Bangladesh, exceeding the height of [[Keokradong]] which is 3,172 feet high.
